---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CTA from '../../components/CTA.astro';
---

<Base
  title="How to Prepare Your Home for EV Charger Installation"
  description="A step-by-step checklist to get your home ready for EV charger installation — from panel checks to garage prep. Bay Area homeowner guide."
>
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-20 md:py-24">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-cover bg-center" style="background-image: url('/images/hero-circuit.webp')">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/60"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="relative max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold mb-4">How to Prepare Your Home for EV Charger Installation</h1>
      <p class="text-white/80 text-lg">A complete checklist from panel assessment to installation day</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <a href="/blog/" class="inline-flex items-center text-primary font-semibold mb-8 hover:underline">&larr; Back to Blog</a>
      <time class="block text-sm text-gray mb-6">March 21, 2026</time>

      <div class="space-y-6 text-gray leading-relaxed">
        <p class="text-lg text-dark font-medium">
          Getting your home ready for an EV charger installation ensures a smooth process, faster completion, and no surprises on installation day. While your electrician handles the technical work, there are several things you can do beforehand to prepare. This checklist covers everything from initial assessment to post-installation verification.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 1: Assess Your Electrical Panel</h2>
        <p>
          Before scheduling installation, take a quick look at your electrical panel. You do not need to be an electrician to gather basic information that helps the process:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Find the main breaker rating:</strong> Open your panel cover and look at the number on the main breaker (top or bottom). It will say 100, 125, 150, or 200. This is your total service amperage.</li>
          <li><strong>Count available spaces:</strong> Look for empty slots where no breaker is installed. A Level 2 EV charger needs a double-pole breaker taking up two spaces.</li>
          <li><strong>Note the panel brand and age:</strong> The manufacturer label is usually inside the panel door. If you see Federal Pacific, Zinsco, or a fuse-based panel, plan for a likely upgrade.</li>
          <li><strong>Take a photo:</strong> A clear photo of your open panel (with the dead front cover removed) helps your electrician assess capacity before the site visit.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If your panel is rated 200A with available spaces, you are in good shape. If it is 100A or has no empty spaces, you may need a panel upgrade (from $3,500) or a sub-panel addition.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 2: Choose Your Charging Location</h2>
        <p>
          Decide where you want the charger mounted. Consider these factors:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Proximity to panel:</strong> Shorter wire runs reduce cost. If your panel is in the garage, mounting the charger on the same wall minimizes installation complexity and expense.</li>
          <li><strong>Vehicle charge port location:</strong> Know which side of your car has the charging port. Position the charger so the cable reaches easily without stretching across the vehicle.</li>
          <li><strong>Wall material:</strong> Drywall, wood studs, concrete, or brick all work but affect mounting hardware. Inform your electrician about the wall material at your preferred location.</li>
          <li><strong>Indoor vs. outdoor:</strong> Indoor garage mounting is simplest. Outdoor mounting requires a weatherproof charger (NEMA 4 rated) and weather-rated conduit, adding slight cost.</li>
          <li><strong>Height:</strong> Most chargers mount between 42-48 inches from the floor, allowing comfortable cable reach without excessive bending. Your electrician will confirm the optimal height.</li>
          <li><strong>Future second vehicle:</strong> If you plan to add a second EV, consider placing the first charger to leave space for a future second unit.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 3: Measure the Wire Run Distance</h2>
        <p>
          Using a tape measure, estimate the distance from your electrical panel to your chosen charger location. Measure along the actual path the wire would travel — through walls, across ceilings, or along exterior surfaces. This does not need to be exact (your electrician will confirm), but knowing whether it is 10 feet or 60 feet helps you anticipate costs.
        </p>
        <p>
          Standard installation at Fox EV Install includes up to 25 feet of conduit and wire. Beyond that, additional footage is charged per foot. Most garage installations where the panel is nearby fall within the standard distance.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 4: Check Your Vehicle Specifications</h2>
        <p>
          Know your vehicle's maximum AC charging acceptance rate:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Tesla Model 3/Y:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Tesla Model S/X:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Rivian R1T/R1S:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Ford Mustang Mach-E:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Chevrolet Bolt EV/EUV:</strong> 32A (7.7 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Hyundai Ioniq 5/6:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>BMW iX/i4:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
          <li><strong>Volkswagen ID.4:</strong> 48A (11.5 kW) maximum</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Matching your charger to your vehicle's maximum acceptance rate ensures you get the fastest possible home charging speed. There is no benefit to a 48A charger if your vehicle can only accept 32A — though future-proofing for your next vehicle is a valid consideration.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 5: Purchase Your Charger (or Let Us Help)</h2>
        <p>
          You can purchase your EV charger before installation day or ask us for a recommendation during your consultation. Popular options for Bay Area homes:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Tesla Wall Connector ($450-$500) — best for Tesla owners</li>
          <li>ChargePoint Home Flex ($550-$650) — best universal charger</li>
          <li>Grizzl-E Classic ($400-$450) — best budget and outdoor option</li>
          <li>JuiceBox 48 ($600-$650) — best for PG&E rate optimization</li>
          <li>Autel MaxiCharger ($500-$600) — best all-around value</li>
          <li>Enphase IQ EV Charger ($1,200-$1,400) — best for Enphase solar homes</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Ensure your charger arrives before the scheduled installation date. Verify it includes all mounting hardware and the installation manual.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 6: Prepare the Installation Area</h2>
        <p>
          On the day before installation, prepare the work area:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Clear the wall area:</strong> Remove shelving, storage bins, tools, or anything mounted within 3 feet of where the charger will go.</li>
          <li><strong>Clear panel access:</strong> Ensure at least 3 feet of clearance in front of your electrical panel (required by code and needed for safe work).</li>
          <li><strong>Move vehicles:</strong> If working in the garage, move cars out to provide full access.</li>
          <li><strong>Secure pets:</strong> Keep dogs and cats away from the work area for their safety and the electrician's efficiency.</li>
          <li><strong>Note WiFi password:</strong> If your charger has WiFi features, have your network name and password ready for setup.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 7: Installation Day Expectations</h2>
        <p>
          A standard EV charger installation typically takes 3-5 hours. Here is what to expect:
        </p>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Electrician arrives, confirms installation plan, and verifies panel capacity</li>
          <li>Power to relevant circuits is temporarily shut off (usually 30-60 minutes)</li>
          <li>New breaker is installed in your panel</li>
          <li>Conduit and wire are run from panel to charger location</li>
          <li>Charger or outlet is mounted and connected</li>
          <li>Power is restored and the system is tested</li>
          <li>Electrician demonstrates charger operation and verifies successful vehicle charging</li>
          <li>Work area is cleaned up and inspection is scheduled</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          You will need to be home (or have someone over 18 present) during installation. The brief power shutoff affects the circuits being worked on — not your entire home in most cases.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Step 8: Post-Installation Checklist</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Test the charger with your vehicle and verify it charges at the expected rate</li>
          <li>Connect the charger to WiFi and set up the app (if applicable)</li>
          <li>Schedule charging for off-peak hours (midnight to 3 PM on PG&E EV-2A)</li>
          <li>Save all documentation: invoice, permit, inspection approval, charger warranty</li>
          <li>File for the federal 30C tax credit (Form 8911) with your next tax return</li>
          <li>Check PG&E residential EV charging rebate eligibility and apply if qualifying</li>
          <li>Switch to PG&E's EV-2A rate plan to maximize charging savings</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-dark pt-4">Ready to Get Started?</h2>
        <p>
          This preparation takes about 30 minutes and ensures your installation proceeds without delays or surprises. If you have questions about any step, contact Fox EV Install for a free consultation. We walk you through the entire process and handle all technical decisions, permitting, and inspection scheduling. Standard installation starts at $1,200 with a dedicated circuit from $550 if needed separately.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTA title="Schedule Your EV Charger Installation" subtitle="Free consultation — we guide you through every step of the process" />
</Base>
